{% set semanticCode %}<!-- Instead of <div class="card"> -->
<article>
  <h3>Card Title</h3>
  <p>Self-contained content.</p>
</article>

<!-- Instead of <div class="sidebar"> -->
<aside>
  <p>Tangentially related content.</p>
</aside>

<!-- Instead of <div class="nav"> -->
<nav aria-label="Primary">
  <ul class="unstyled">
    <li><a href="#">Home</a></li>
  </ul>
</nav>

<!-- Instead of <div class="footer"> / <div class="actions"> -->
<footer>
  <button type="button">Save</button>
</footer>{% endset %}

{% set layoutCode %}<!-- Instead of <div data-layout="stack"> -->
<section data-layout="stack" data-layout-gap="m">
  <p>Content with vertical spacing.</p>
  <p>No wrapper div needed.</p>
</section>

<!-- Instead of <div data-layout="grid"> -->
<ul data-layout="grid" data-layout-gap="m">
  <li>Grid item one</li>
  <li>Grid item two</li>
</ul>{% endset %}

{% set legitimateCode %}<!-- dl grouping (HTML5 spec allows div inside dl) -->
<dl data-striped>
  <div>
    <dt>Term</dt>
    <dd>Description</dd>
  </div>
</dl>

<!-- Radio/checkbox group wrapper for form-field -->
<form-field>
  <fieldset>
    <legend>Options</legend>
    <div>
      <label><input type="radio" name="opt" /> Option A</label>
      <label><input type="radio" name="opt" /> Option B</label>
    </div>
  </fieldset>
</form-field>{% endset %}

{% set conformanceCode %}# VB conformance checker flags divs:

vb/no-div          — Any <div> element (warning → error)
vb/no-div-wrapper   — <div> wrapping a single semantic child
semantic/no-div     — Semantic check for div elements{% endset %}

<section>
    <h2>Philosophy</h2>
    <p>Vanilla Breeze takes an intentional stance: <strong><code>&lt;div&gt;</code> is a last resort, not a default.</strong> The VB conformance checker flags every <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> as a warning, and the semantic check raises it as an error for new code.</p>
    <p>This is not about being pedantic &mdash; semantic elements provide:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Accessibility:</strong> Screen readers can navigate by landmarks (<code>&lt;nav&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;main&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code>)</li>
      <li><strong>SEO:</strong> Search engines understand content structure from semantic markup</li>
      <li><strong>Readability:</strong> Code is self-documenting when elements describe their purpose</li>
      <li><strong>Less CSS:</strong> VB styles semantic elements directly &mdash; no class soup</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Semantic Alternatives</h2>
    <p>For every common <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> pattern, a semantic element exists:</p>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/div-alternatives.html" url="div-alternatives.html" title="Semantic alternatives" shadow></browser-window>

    <table class="props-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Instead of</th><th>Use</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>&lt;div class="card"&gt;</code></td><td><a href="/docs/elements/native/article/"><code>&lt;article&gt;</code></a></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>&lt;div class="sidebar"&gt;</code></td><td><a href="/docs/elements/native/aside/"><code>&lt;aside&gt;</code></a></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>&lt;div class="nav"&gt;</code></td><td><a href="/docs/elements/native/nav/"><code>&lt;nav&gt;</code></a></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>&lt;div class="header"&gt;</code></td><td><a href="/docs/elements/native/header/"><code>&lt;header&gt;</code></a></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>&lt;div class="footer"&gt;</code></td><td><a href="/docs/elements/native/footer/"><code>&lt;footer&gt;</code></a></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>&lt;div class="main"&gt;</code></td><td><a href="/docs/elements/native/main/"><code>&lt;main&gt;</code></a></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>&lt;div class="section"&gt;</code></td><td><a href="/docs/elements/native/section/"><code>&lt;section&gt;</code></a></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>&lt;div class="actions"&gt;</code></td><td><code>&lt;footer&gt;</code> or <a href="/docs/elements/native/menu/"><code>&lt;menu&gt;</code></a></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>&lt;div class="group"&gt;</code></td><td><a href="/docs/elements/native/fieldset/"><code>&lt;fieldset&gt;</code></a></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>&lt;div data-layout="stack"&gt;</code></td><td>Put <code>data-layout</code> on the semantic parent</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Semantic replacements">{{ semanticCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Layout Without Divs</h2>
    <p>VB's layout attributes (<code>data-layout</code>) and custom elements (<code>&lt;layout-stack&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;layout-grid&gt;</code>, etc.) can be applied directly to semantic elements:</p>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Layout on semantic elements">{{ layoutCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <p>When no semantic element fits, VB layout custom elements (<code>&lt;layout-stack&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;layout-grid&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;layout-cluster&gt;</code>) serve as the container &mdash; they are more descriptive than <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> because they declare layout intent.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Legitimate Uses</h2>
    <p>There are a few cases where <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> is the correct choice:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong><code>&lt;dl&gt;</code> grouping:</strong> HTML5 allows <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> inside <code>&lt;dl&gt;</code> to group <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code>/<code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> pairs (for striped styling)</li>
      <li><strong>Form field groups:</strong> Wrapping radio/checkbox groups inside <code>&lt;form-field&gt;</code></li>
      <li><strong>Third-party widgets:</strong> When external libraries require a container div</li>
      <li><strong>CSS Grid/Flex children:</strong> When you genuinely need a non-semantic grid cell</li>
    </ul>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Legitimate div uses">{{ legitimateCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Conformance Enforcement</h2>
    <p>VB enforces semantic HTML through automated tooling:</p>

    <code-block language="text" label="Conformance rules">{{ conformanceCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <ul>
      <li><strong><code>vb/no-div</code></strong> &mdash; Flags any <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> element. Suggests semantic alternatives.</li>
      <li><strong><code>vb/no-div-wrapper</code></strong> &mdash; Flags <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> wrapping a single semantic child (the div is unnecessary).</li>
      <li><strong>Allowlist:</strong> Known legitimate uses can be added to <code>.claude/vb-conformance-allowlist.json</code></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Run <code>npm run conformance</code> to check your HTML files.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The VB Refinement Checklist</h2>
    <p>When auditing existing code with divs, follow this order:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Div audit:</strong> Can each div be replaced with a semantic element?</li>
      <li><strong>Wrapper audit:</strong> Is a div wrapping a single child that could receive the attributes directly?</li>
      <li><strong>data-layout audit:</strong> Is <code>data-layout</code> on a div when it could be on the semantic parent?</li>
      <li><strong>Class audit:</strong> Are VB element-scoped classes available (e.g., <code>form.stacked</code>)?</li>
      <li><strong>Semantic opportunities:</strong> Can <code>&lt;footer&gt;</code> replace a button group div? Can <code>&lt;header&gt;</code> replace a title wrapper?</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><code>&lt;div&gt;</code> has no implicit ARIA role &mdash; it is invisible to screen readers</li>
      <li>Screen readers cannot navigate by divs; they <em>can</em> navigate by landmarks, headings, lists, and other semantic elements</li>
      <li>Every div you replace with a semantic element improves the accessibility tree</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

